questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;Correct option-&lt;b&gt;1&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Circular Motion&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An object is said to perform a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;circular motion&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;when it moves on a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;circular path&lt;/span&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While describing circular motion we often use the term&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;circular motion&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of point object or particle.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is because we learn circular motion with the brach of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;translation motion&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of a body on a circular path and disregard any&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;rotation.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, we represent the body as a particle.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Circular motion&lt;/strong&gt; is classified into two categories&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;1.Uniform circular motion:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If a particle moves with a constant speed in a circle, then the motion is called&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;uniform circular&amp;nbsp;motion.&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In uniform-circular motion, particle possesses only centripetal acceleration&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;(a&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;r&lt;/span&gt;).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/22/09/F3_Madhuri_Defence_30.09.2022_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 250px; height: 209px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;2.Non-uniform circular motion:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the particle moves with variable speed then the motion is called&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;non-uniform motion.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In uniform-circular motion, particle possesses two kinds of acceleration.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/22/09/F3_Madhuri_Defence_30.09.2022_D2.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 250px; height: 209px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;(i) Centripetal acceleration (a&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;r&lt;/span&gt;)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;amp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;(ii) Tangential acceleration (a&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;t&lt;/span&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In a uniform circular motion, particle performing motion along the circular path has only radial or centripetal acceleration (a&lt;sub&gt;r&lt;/sub&gt;).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We know that from newton&amp;#39;s law of motion, Net force act on a body will be equal to mass time acceleration,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;i.e, F = ma&lt;sub&gt;c&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;(centripetal force). So, here centripetal force is always required to keep a particle in a circular path with uniform speed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, option-&lt;b&gt;1&lt;/b&gt;&amp;nbsp;is correct&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Velocity: &lt;/strong&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;rate of change of displacement&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;of a body is called as&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;velocity&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;of that body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;vector quantity&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;which has both&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;magnitude&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;as well as&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;direction&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(Velocity\left( V \right) = \frac{{Change\;in\;displacement}}{{Time\;taken}} = \frac{{{S_2} - {S_1}}}{{{t_2} - {t_1}}}\;or\;\frac{{dS}}{{dt}}\;\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where S&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;is final displacement at time t&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;and S&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;is initial displacement at time t&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acceleration: &lt;/strong&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;rate of change of velocity&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is called as&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;acceleration&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the body.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(a = \frac{{v2 - v1}}{{t2 - t1}}\;or\;\frac{{dv}}{{dt}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where v&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;= Final velocity and v&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;= Initial velocity of an object at time&amp;nbsp;t&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;, t&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; respectively&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;acceleration is a vector quantity&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;so&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;constant acceleration means&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;both&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;magnitudes&lt;/strong&gt;, as well as the direction of the acceleration of the body, is the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;same&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If there will be any&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;change in the path of the body&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;then the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;direction of the body will change&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;and hence the direction of the velocity will change so the velocity will&amp;nbsp;not be constant which will cause to generate&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;acceleration. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;For example,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;In the case of uniform&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;circular motion,&lt;/strong&gt; the &lt;strong&gt;direction of the velocity&lt;/strong&gt; always &lt;strong&gt;changes&lt;/strong&gt; which causes the&lt;strong&gt; generation of centripetal acceleration&lt;/strong&gt; which will be &lt;strong&gt;directed towards its center &lt;/strong&gt;and it will be &lt;strong&gt;constant magnitude&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;, therefore, &lt;strong&gt;option&amp;nbsp;3&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt; incorrect&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Since, the acceleration (a) is written as:&lt;strong&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(a = \frac{{{v_2} - {v_1}}}{{{t_2} - {t_1}}}\;or\;\frac{{dv}}{{dt}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;hence&amp;nbsp;if &lt;strong&gt;acceleration is constant&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;so&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;the rate of change of acceleration will be zero.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(i.e.,\frac{{da}}{{dt}} = 0\)&lt;/span&gt;, this means that acceleration won&amp;rsquo;t change with time therefore &lt;strong&gt;option 2 &lt;/strong&gt;is &lt;strong&gt;correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the velocity is varying linearly with time then also the acceleration will be constant so &lt;strong&gt;option 1 &lt;/strong&gt;will also be &lt;strong&gt;incorrect&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; v = kt &amp;rArr; a = k = Constant&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 2.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:.5in;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Frequency: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It&amp;#39;s defined as the number of oscillations per unit of time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Frequency = (Number of Oscillations)/ (Time taken)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Time period:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It&amp;#39;s defined as the time required to complete one oscillation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Time Period = (Time taken) / (Number of Oscillations)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Calculation&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Time = 30 sec, Number of oscillations = 120&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Frequency = (Number of Oscillations)/ (Time taken)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Frequency = 120/30 = 4 Hz&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Time Period = (Time taken) / (Number of Oscillations)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;= 30/120 = 1/4 = 0.25&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence Frequency: Time period = 4: 1/4 =&amp;nbsp; 16:1&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 4.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Tangential acceleration:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In a circular motion, the component of the acceleration directed along the tangent of the circle is called tangential acceleration.&lt;/strong&gt; Tangential acceleration is responsible for changing the speed of the particle.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Centripetal acceleration:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In a circular motion, the component of the acceleration directed along the radius of the circle is called centripetal acceleration.&lt;/strong&gt; It is responsible for the change in direction of velocity. It is always variable because due to this acceleration, the direction of the particle changes continuously.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A particle moving in a circle of radius r with constant speed V undergoes a centripetal (or radial) acceleration because the direction of V changes in time.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The magnitude of t&lt;strong&gt;he acceleration is given by a &lt;/strong&gt;=&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\dfrac{V^2}{r}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
