&lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-114&quot; type=&quot;math/mml&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mrow data-mjx-texclass=&quot;ORD&quot;&gt;&lt;munder&gt;&lt;mi&gt;​&lt;merror&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;Unknown node type: span&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;/merror&gt;&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/munder&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-8&quot; type=&quot;math/mml&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mrow data-mjx-texclass=&quot;ORD&quot;&gt;&lt;munder&gt;&lt;mi&gt;​&lt;merror&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;Unknown node type: span&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;/merror&gt;&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/munder&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/script&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-79&quot; type=&quot;math/mml&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mrow data-mjx-texclass=&quot;ORD&quot;&gt;&lt;munder&gt;&lt;mi&gt;​&lt;merror&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;Unknown node type: span&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;/merror&gt;&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/munder&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/script&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;script id=&quot;MathJax-Element-39&quot; type=&quot;math/mml&quot;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mrow data-mjx-texclass=&quot;ORD&quot;&gt;&lt;mover&gt;&lt;mi&gt;​&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;&lt;mjx-container class=&quot;MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0&quot; ctxtmenu_counter=&quot;3&quot; jax=&quot;CHTML&quot; style=&quot;line-height: 0; font-size: 19.12px; position: relative;&quot; tabindex=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;mjx-assistive-mml display=&quot;inline&quot; style=&quot;top: 0px; left: 0px; clip: rect(1px, 1px, 1px, 1px); user-select: none; position: absolute !important; padding: 1px 0px 0px !important; border: 0px !important; display: block !important; width: auto !important; overflow: hidden !important;&quot; unselectable=&quot;on&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; data-cke-saved-src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F1_J.K_Madhu_19.05.20_D1.png&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F1_J.K_Madhu_19.05.20_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 288px; height: 235px;&quot;&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;ul style=&quot;color: rgb(30, 43, 51); font-family: RobotoRegular, acumin-pro, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, &amp;quot;Segoe UI&amp;quot;, &amp;quot;Helvetica Neue&amp;quot;, Arial, &amp;quot;Noto Sans&amp;quot;, sans-serif, &amp;quot;Apple Color Emoji&amp;quot;, &amp;quot;Segoe UI Emoji&amp;quot;, &amp;quot;Segoe UI Symbol&amp;quot;, &amp;quot;Noto Color Emoji&amp;quot;; font-size: 16px; white-space: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/mjx-assistive-mml&gt;&lt;/mjx-container&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mover&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/script&gt; &lt;/mjx-assistive-mml&gt;&lt;/mjx-container&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Concept&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Projectile motion:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A&amp;nbsp;kind of&amp;nbsp;motion that is&amp;nbsp;experienced by an object when it&amp;nbsp;is projected near the Earth&amp;#39;s surface and moves along a curved path under the action of gravitational force.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F2_J.K_Madhu_04.05.20__D3.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 413px; height: 238px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;maximum height a projectile&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;can attain:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(H = \frac{{{u^2}{{\sin }^2}θ }}{{2g}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The maximum &lt;strong&gt;Range of projectile&lt;/strong&gt; is given as:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(⇒R=\frac{u^2\sin~2θ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where u is the&amp;nbsp;velocity that makes an angle &amp;#39;&amp;theta;&amp;#39; with the x-axis, and g is the gravitational acceleration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Calculation&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When the projectile has initial velocity &lt;strong&gt;u&lt;/strong&gt; and is launched at&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;theta;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;angle it has range&lt;strong&gt; R.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(R=\frac{u^2\sin~2θ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp; ........(1)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now initial velocity is doubled so the new velocity is&lt;strong&gt; v = 2u&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;and the new range in &lt;strong&gt;R&lt;sub&gt;N&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(∴R_N=\frac{v^2\sin~2θ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(∴R_N=\frac{(2u)^2\sin~2θ}{g}=\frac{4v^2 \sin~2θ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(∴R_N=4\times \frac{v^2\sin~2θ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp; (∵ from eq 1)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;there4; R&lt;sub&gt;N&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sub&gt;= 4R&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;So while the initial velocity becomes double the range becomes 4 times the previous range.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Projectile motion:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;A&amp;nbsp;kind of&amp;nbsp;motion that is&amp;nbsp;experienced by an object when it&amp;nbsp;is projected near the Earth&amp;#39;s surface and moves along a curved path under the action of gravitational force.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F2_J.K_Madhu_04.05.20__D3.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 413px; height: 238px;&quot; /&gt;​&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;body moves in projectile motion&lt;/strong&gt; if its&lt;strong&gt; acceleration is constant &lt;/strong&gt;and the&lt;strong&gt; velocity is not in the direction of the acceleration.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&lt;strong&gt; ball will follow the motion of a projectile.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When the ball is dropped from the bus, it has an initial velocity that is the same as the bus.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So the ball has an initial velocity in the horizontal direction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;And it will have acceleration in the downward direction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Since it has a speed in the horizontal direction and constant gravitational acceleration in the vertical direction, so the ball will follow a&amp;nbsp;projectile trajectory.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 3.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Calculation&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given that, v =&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;36km/h (36 &amp;times; (1000/3600)) = 10 m/s&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;, u =&amp;nbsp;72km/h (72 &amp;times; (1000/3600)) = 20 m/s, t = 10 sec&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Here, acceleration = Rate of change of velocity/time&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;= 20&amp;nbsp;- 10 / 10&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;= 10/10 = 1 m/s&lt;sup&gt;2&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In&amp;nbsp;Uniform Circular Motion the velocity of the body remains constant&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Uniform Circular Motion&lt;/strong&gt; the velocity of a body remains constant is the&lt;strong&gt; incorrect &lt;/strong&gt;option for&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;uniform circular motion&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(11, 24, 47);&quot;&gt;.&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(11, 24, 47);&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(11, 24, 47);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​Uniform circular motion&lt;/strong&gt; can be described as the motion of an object in a circle at a &lt;strong&gt;constant speed.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As an object moves in a circle, it is constantly changing its direction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Although the &lt;strong&gt;speed&lt;/strong&gt; of the &lt;strong&gt;body&lt;/strong&gt; remains the &lt;strong&gt;same&lt;/strong&gt; the &lt;strong&gt;velocity is changing &lt;/strong&gt;due to &lt;strong&gt;the change in direction.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An object moving in a circle is accelerating.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Accelerating objects&lt;/strong&gt; are objects which are&lt;strong&gt; changing their velocity&lt;/strong&gt; either the speed&lt;strong&gt; (magnitude of the velocity vector)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;or&lt;strong&gt; the direction.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An object undergoing uniform circular motion is moving at a constant speed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Nonetheless, it is accelerating due to its change in direction.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Projectile Motion:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a particle is thrown obliquely near the earth&amp;rsquo;s surface, it moves along a curved path under constant acceleration directed towards the center of the earth. The path of such a particle is called a projectile, and the motion is called projectile motion&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;​&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/23/02/F10_Vinanti_Teaching_08.02.23_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 202px; width: 346px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Maximum height,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(H=\frac{u^2sin^2θ}{2g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Horizontal range,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(R=\frac{u^2sin2θ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Time of flight,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(T=\frac{2usinθ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, u = the initial velocity of the projectile, g = acceleration due to gravity,&amp;nbsp;&amp;theta; = angle of projection&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The angle of projection for body&amp;nbsp;A,&amp;nbsp;&amp;theta; = 30&amp;ordm;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The angle of projection for body B,&amp;nbsp;&amp;theta; = 60&amp;ordm;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Horizontal range,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(R=\frac{u^2sin2θ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The ratio of the horizontal range of body A to&amp;nbsp; body B will be:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{R_A}{R_B}=\frac{\frac{u^2sin(2\theta_A)}{g}}{\frac{u^2sin(2\theta_B)}{g}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{R_A}{R_B}=\frac{sin(2\theta_A)}{sin(2\theta_B)}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{R_A}{R_B}=\frac{sin(2\times 30)}{sin(2\times 60)}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{R_A}{R_B}=\frac{sin60}{sin120}=1\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ratio, R&lt;sub&gt;A&lt;/sub&gt;: R&lt;sub&gt;B&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1: 1&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A position vector is defined as a vector that symbolizes either the position or the location of any given point with respect to any arbitrary reference point like the origin. The direction of the position vector always points from the origin of that vector toward a given point.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Velocity defines the direction of the movement of the body or the object. Speed is primarily a scalar quantity. Velocity is essentially a vector quantity. It is the rate of change of distance. It is the rate of change of displacement.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(v = {dx\over dt}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Acceleration is the&amp;nbsp;rate at which velocity changes with time, in terms of both speed and direction. A point or an object moving in a straight line is accelerated if it speeds up or slows down. Motion on a circle is accelerated even if the speed is constant because the direction is continually changing.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(a = {dv\over dt}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;v(t) = (1 -&amp;nbsp;3t&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ 2t&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;) m/s&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;its position at t = 0 is x = 0 then at t = 2 s, its position is to be calculated.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Since,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(v = {dx\over dt}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( {dx\over dt} = 1-3t^2+2t^3\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\int_{0}^x dx = \int_{0}^t{(1-3t^2+2t^3})dt\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(x = {(t-t^3+0.5t^4})\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(x_{(t=2s)} = 2-2^3+0.5\times 2^4\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(x_{(t=2s)} = 2-8+8\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(x_{(t=2s)} = 2~ m\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Distance:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The complete length of the path between any two points.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a scalar quantity because it has only magnitude.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To calculate distance, the direction is not considered.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Displacement:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The direct length between any two points when measured along the minimum path between them.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a vector quantity because it has both magnitude and direction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To calculate displacement, the direction is taken into consideration.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The radius of the circle, r = 1m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The distance (Displacement) of AB can be calculated from the Pythagotous theorem,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;AB&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;= AC&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ CB&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(AB=\sqrt{1^2+1^2}= \sqrt{2} ~m \)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(AB=\sqrt{2} ~m \)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Distance = 3/4(2&amp;pi;r)&amp;nbsp;= 1.5&amp;nbsp;&amp;pi;r&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Distance = 1.5&amp;nbsp;&amp;pi;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Under&amp;nbsp;free&amp;nbsp;fall where gravity is the sole influence on the body, the total energy remains the same&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Potential energy gets converted into the kinetic energy&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Potential Energy keeps on decreasing and kinetic energy keeps on increasing&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is also in confirmation with the law of conservation of energy&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F4_J.S_9.5.20_Pallavi_D2.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 350px; height: 157px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From the given condition we know that body is falling freely under the influence of gravity&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence the equation of velocity can be predicted using any of the two methods given below&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;By conservation of energy:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So as explained above if a body is under free fall the energy of the system remains conserved&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;i.e., Potential energy = Kinetic energy&lt;br /&gt;
	&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(mgh = \frac{1}{2}m{v^2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;using this relation, we can find the velocity of the object at any instance&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;By kinematic equation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Similarly, we can use the kinematic equation as well to solve such problems&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Just like in this case as the object starts falling its initial velocity must be zero&lt;br /&gt;
	i.e., u = 0&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;And as an object falling it will be accelerated due to gravitational force, and its rate of acceleration is given by g&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the velocity of the object at any instance can be predicted using &lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({v^2} = {u^2} + 2aS\)&lt;/span&gt;, here S (displacement) is height so we can assume it as h&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;there4; &lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({v^2} = 0 + 2gh \Rightarrow v = \sqrt {2gh} \)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If an object is traveling in a straight line parallel to each other then there exist two cases of relative velocity&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Case 1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;relative&amp;nbsp;velocity&amp;nbsp;of 2 objects moving toward&amp;nbsp; or away each other in opposite direction,&amp;nbsp; V&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;&quot;&gt;relative&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is given by&lt;br /&gt;
	V&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;&quot;&gt;relative&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;= |v&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ v&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;|&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F4_J.S_9.5.20_Pallavi_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 305px; height: 153px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Case 2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;relative&amp;nbsp;velocity&amp;nbsp;of 2 objects moving along the same&amp;nbsp;direction, V&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;&quot;&gt;relative&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is&amp;nbsp;given by&lt;br /&gt;
	V&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;&quot;&gt;relative&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;= |v&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;- v&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;|&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Similarly, if two objects A and B are traveling perpendicular to each other&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F4_J.S_9.5.20_Pallavi_D3.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 183px; height: 127px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here relative velocity can be easily calculated using Pythagoras theorem&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;i.e.,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({V_{relative}} = \sqrt {\;({v_a} + {v_b})\;} \)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Calculation:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&amp;nbsp;boat&amp;nbsp;is traveling perpendicular to the&amp;nbsp;river&amp;nbsp;so the flow of&amp;nbsp;the river&amp;nbsp;does not affect the&amp;nbsp;speed&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;the boat&amp;nbsp;in its direction but it carries the&amp;nbsp;boat&amp;nbsp;perpendicular to the direction of&amp;nbsp;the boat&amp;nbsp;with&amp;nbsp;a speed&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;the river&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The distance moved by&amp;nbsp;boat&amp;nbsp;will be the hypotenuse of the right triangle so formed by the two&amp;nbsp;speeds&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Distance moved in one hour = 50/2 = 25 km&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let&amp;nbsp;Speed&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;the river&amp;nbsp;be R and&amp;nbsp;Speed&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;boat&amp;nbsp;be B.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; 25&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;= R&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ B&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;(Pythagoras theorem)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; 625 = R&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ B&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also, B - R = 17&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;-----(1)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Squaring both sides, we get&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; B&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ R&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;ndash; 2 &amp;times; R &amp;times; B = 289&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; 625 &amp;ndash; 2 &amp;times; R &amp;times; B = 289&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; 2 &amp;times; R &amp;times; B = 336&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; (B + R)&amp;nbsp;&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;= B&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ R&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ 2 &amp;times; R &amp;times; B = 625 + 336 = 961&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; B + R = 31&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;-----(2)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From (1) and (2), we get&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; B = 24 km/h and R = 7 km/h&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;there4;&amp;nbsp;The speed&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;boat&amp;nbsp;is 24 km/hr and&amp;nbsp;River&amp;nbsp;is 7 km/hr.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Consider the following figure:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/04/F1_J.S_6.4.20_Pallavi_D2.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 238px; height: 168px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Which of the following labelled points in the figure given above indicate an unstable state of an object?&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;From the given graph we can see that the potential energy is minimum at point B and D&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Whereas it has &lt;strong&gt;maximum potential energy&lt;/strong&gt; at point A and C respectively&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence point A and C will be an unstable state since they have maximum potential energy compared to B and D.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;CONCEPT:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The equation of motion for a body motion in a straight line are&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;v = u + at&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;s = ut +&amp;nbsp;&amp;frac12;at2&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;v2 - u2 = 2as&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where u and v are initial and final velocities, a is the acceleration and t is the time taken.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;EXPLANATION:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/23/02/F1_Vinanti_Teaching_10.02.23_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 175px; width: 195px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;As the figure shows let the distance traveled in the horizontal and vertical directions are x and y respectively.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr;&lt;/span&gt; y/x = tan&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;45&amp;deg;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; y/x = 1&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; y = x ---- (1)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Again, The equation of motion along x-axis,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; x = u&lt;sub&gt;x&lt;/sub&gt; t (where, u&lt;sub&gt;x&lt;/sub&gt; = initial velocity along x-axis&lt;/span&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; x = 5t (∵&amp;nbsp;u&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 5 m/s) ---- (2)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Again, The equation of motion along y-axis,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; y = u&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt; t +&amp;nbsp;&amp;frac12; gt&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; y = 0&amp;times;t +&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;frac12; g(x/5)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;[using equation 2]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; y = gx&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;/50&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; y = gy&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;/50&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;gy&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;/50 - y = 0&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; y (gy/50 - 1) = 0&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;So, y = 0 or,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;gy/50 - 1 = 0&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; y = 50/g&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;there4; x = 50/g [using equation 1]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;So, the total distance traveled &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; d =&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( \sqrt{x^2 + y^2 } \sqrt{x^2 + y^2 } = \sqrt{ (50/g)^2 + (50/g)^2 } = \sqrt{ 2(50/g)^2}= \sqrt{2} (50/g)\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; d = 7.07 m&amp;nbsp;&amp;asymp; 7.1 m/s&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Hence the correct answer is option (2).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct option-3&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;INSTANTANEOUS VELOCITY&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The velocity of a moving object at a particular instant of time is called instantaneous velocity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We can define velocity at a particular instant as the limiting value of average velocity when time interval ∆t approaches zero.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mathematically we can write the same as follows:&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(v=\underset{\Delta t\to 0}{\mathop{\lim }}\,\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta t}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When we calculate average velocity or speed the selected time interval can be large or small.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;But when the time interval selected is infinitesimally small then it is known as instantaneous velocity or speed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For a moving object, the instantaneous speed at any point is equal to the magnitude of instantaneous velocity,&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;but the average speed in a given time interval is always greater or equal to the magnitude of average velocity in that interval.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The slope of the position-time graph gives us velocity at a given instant of time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the case of non-uniform motion, the curve of the position-time graph is not linear or straight.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, slope in this case given by a tangent to the curve at a particular instant of time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;therefore, the position-time graph gives us velocity called instantaneous velocity.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/23/09/F4_Vinanti_Teaching_11.09.23_D15.png&quot; style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41); width: 192px; height: 164px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, option-3 is correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pythagorean theorem, the well-known geometric theorem that the sum of the squares on the legs of a right triangle is equal to the square on the hypotenuse (the side opposite the right angle)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;a&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + b&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; = c&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Solution:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/22/12/F1_Vinanti_Teaching_08.12.22_D3.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 326px; width: 417px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let AB be the displacement of the person towards the North, BC be the displacement towards the east&amp;nbsp;and CE be the displacement in the South-West direction. We have to find the displacement of the person from the origin, EA&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Consider the right triangle &amp;Delta; ECD, by Pythagoras&amp;#39; theorem&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;ED&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ CD&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;= EC&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;rarr; (i)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From fig, CD=AB=30m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;EC=30&amp;radic;2&amp;nbsp;m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;ED=EA+AD&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;AD=BC=20m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;there4;ED=EA+20m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(i)&amp;rarr;(EA+20)&lt;sup&gt;2&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sup&gt;+ (30)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;= (30&amp;radic;2)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(EA+20)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ 900&amp;nbsp; = 1800&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;EA+20=30&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;EA=10m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is option (3).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Projectile motion&lt;/strong&gt; is a form of motion in which an object or particle is thrown near the earth&amp;#39;s surface, and it moves along a curved path under the action of gravity only.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Time of flight,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(T =\frac{2usinθ}g\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Range, it&amp;nbsp;is the distance travelled by the particle in time T.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(R = \frac{u^2sin2θ}g\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Maximum height reached,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(H = \frac{u^2sin^2θ}{2g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Where, u = initial speed,&amp;nbsp;&amp;theta; = angle from horizontal,&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Calculation:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given data,&amp;nbsp;&amp;theta;&amp;nbsp;= 30&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt;, u =&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;13 m s&lt;sup&gt;-1&lt;/sup&gt;,&amp;nbsp;g = 10 m.s&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;-2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Since the height of thrown of ball and point where distance is to be calculated is same, then the total distance covered is equal to range.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(R = \frac{u^2sin2θ}g\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(R = \frac{(13)^2sin2\times30}{10}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;rArr; &lt;strong&gt;R = 14.6358 m&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Projectile motion&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When a particle is thrown obliquely near the earth&amp;#39;s surface, it moves along a curved path under constant acceleration that is directed towards centre of earth.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The path of such particle is called &amp;#39;Projectile&amp;#39; and motion is called &amp;#39;projectile motion&amp;#39;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/03/F1_Tapesh_18-03-21_Shraddha_D8.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 414px; height: 232px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Total time of flight (t)&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(= \dfrac{2u sin θ }{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Horizontal Range (R)&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(= \dfrac{u^2 sin 2θ }{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Maximum height (H&lt;sub&gt;max&lt;/sub&gt;)&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(= \dfrac{u^2 sin^2 θ}{2g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given that Range is 3 times maximum height and &amp;#39;u&amp;#39; is velocity of projectile of projectile.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From above equation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;R = 3 H&lt;sub&gt;max&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\dfrac{u^2 sin 2θ }{g}= \dfrac{3 \times u^2 sin^2 θ}{2g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(2 sin θ cos θ = \dfrac {3 (sin θ ) ( sin θ)}{2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\dfrac{cos θ}{sin θ}= \dfrac{3}{4}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/03/F1_Tapesh_18-03-21_Shraddha_D9.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 153px; height: 117px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;sin&amp;nbsp;&amp;theta; = 4/5&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Total time of flight (t)&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(= \dfrac{2u sin θ }{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(= \dfrac{2u \frac{4}{5}}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(= \dfrac{8u}{5g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;option 1 is correct&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;​When a vehicle takes a turn on a circular path it requires centripetal force. If friction provides this centripetal force then the vehicle can move in a circular path safely.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Friction force &amp;ge; Required centripetal force.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the maximum friction provided by the ground and the tires are less than the required centripetal force then it will not be able to take a perfect turn as expected and it will try to leave out the circle i.e. it will skid away.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The centripetal acceleration a&lt;sub&gt;c&lt;/sub&gt; has a magnitude equal to the square of the body&amp;#39;s speed v along the curve divided by the distance r from the center of the circle to the moving body. Centripetal acceleration has units of meters per second squared.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tangential acceleration is the rate at which a tangential velocity varies in the rotational motion of any object. It acts in the direction of a tangent at the point of motion for an object. The tangential velocity also acts in the same direction for an object undergoing circular motion.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The free-body diagram of the motion of the car is as follows,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/22/10/F1_Madhuri_Defence_21.10.2022_D13.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 238px; height: 184px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Equation of motion are as follows,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For the vertical motion:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(ma_t = {μ mgcosθ}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(μ gcos\theta =3\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(cos\theta = {3\over \mu g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;..............(1)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For the horizontal motion:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(μ mgsin\theta = {mv^2 \over r}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(μ gsin\theta = {v^2 \over r}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(sin\theta = {v^2 \over r\mu g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;............(2)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;squaring (1) &amp;amp; (2), we get&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({9 \over ({\mu g})^2} + {v^4 \over ({\mu gr})^2}= sin^2\theta + cos^2\theta\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;where&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(sin^2\theta + cos^2\theta = 1\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({9 \over ({0.5 \times 10})^2} + {v^4 \over ({0.5\times 10 \times 16})^2}= 1\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( {v^4 \over ({0.5\times 10 \times 16})^2}= 1 -{9 \over 25}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( {v^4 \over ({80})^2}= {16 \over 25}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( {v^4}= {16 \over 25}(6400)\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;v&lt;sup&gt;4&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sup&gt;= 4096&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;v = 8 m/s&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;This is the required velocity.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A projectile can have the same range if the angles of projection are complementary, i.e., &amp;theta; and (90&amp;deg; &amp;minus; &amp;theta;).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/25/08/f132bf860ed77243f8f03cfbff6b5a81-.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 326px; height: 197px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In both cases, the time of flight is:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;t&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 2u sin&amp;theta; / g ... (i)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;t&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = 2u sin(90&amp;deg; &amp;minus; &amp;theta;) / g = 2u cos&amp;theta; / g ... (ii)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From Eqs. (i) and (ii):&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;t&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;times; t&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = (2u sin&amp;theta; / g) &amp;times; (2u cos&amp;theta; / g) = 4u&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; sin&amp;theta; cos&amp;theta; / g&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Using the trigonometric identity 2 sin&amp;theta; cos&amp;theta; = sin2&amp;theta;, we get:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;t&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;times; t&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = 2u&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; sin2&amp;theta; / g&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Since the range R = u&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; sin2&amp;theta; / g, we have:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;t&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;times; t&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = 2R / g&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the product of the times of flight for complementary angles is directly proportional to the range R.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Gravitational potential energy is maximum at the highest point:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;At the highest point, height (h) is maximum, so U = m &amp;times; g &amp;times; h is maximum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Correct statement.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;The horizontal component of velocity is zero at the highest point:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Horizontal velocity (v&lt;sub&gt;x&lt;/sub&gt;) is constant throughout the motion (no horizontal acceleration).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Incorrect statement.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;The vertical component of momentum is maximum at the highest point:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;At the highest point, vertical velocity (v&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt;) = 0, so vertical momentum = m &amp;times; v&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt; = 0.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Incorrect statement.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;The kinetic energy (K.E.) is zero at the highest point:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;At the highest point, horizontal velocity (v&lt;sub&gt;x&lt;/sub&gt;) is still present, so K.E. &amp;ne; 0.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Incorrect statement.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;there4; The correct answer is Option 1: Gravitational potential energy is maximum at the highest point.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;line-height:1.6; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;line-height:1.6; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/25/07/f442c24c-f317-4366-b094-e7657b0ebd8e_removalai_preview.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; height: 247px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/25/08/IMG-1630-Arpit-12.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 380px; height: 416px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;line-height:1.6; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt;&quot;&gt;f = (m&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; v&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;) / r&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;line-height:1.6; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt;&quot;&gt;For maximum speed in safe turning:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;line-height:1.6; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt;&quot;&gt;f&lt;sub&gt;s&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sub&gt;max&lt;/sub&gt; = &amp;mu;mg&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;line-height:1.6; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt;&quot;&gt;V&lt;sub&gt;max&lt;/sub&gt; (for safe turning) = &amp;radic;(&amp;mu;rg)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;line-height:1.6; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt;&quot;&gt;= &amp;radic;(0.34 &amp;times; 50 &amp;times; 10) = 13 m/s&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Projectile motion:&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;A&amp;nbsp;kind of&amp;nbsp;motion that is&amp;nbsp;experienced by an object when it&amp;nbsp;is projected near the Earth&amp;#39;s surface and it moves along a curved path under the action of gravitational force.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;maximum height a projectile&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;can attain:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(H = \frac{{u_y^2}}{{2g}} = \frac{{{u^2}{{\sin }^2}θ }}{{2g}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where u is the&amp;nbsp;velocity that makes an angle &amp;#39;&amp;theta;&amp;#39; with the x-axis, and g is the gravitational acceleration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a particle&amp;nbsp;moves in projectile motion, its&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;velocity has two components.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ol style=&quot;margin-left: 40px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;​​vertical component (u sin&amp;theta;) = u&lt;sub&gt;x&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;horizontal component (u cos&amp;theta;) = u&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F2_J.K_Madhu_04.05.20__D3.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 413px; height: 238px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let the maximum height attained by the projectile is H,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At the maximum height, the ball will have zero velocity in vertical&amp;nbsp;direction i.e. v&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt; = 0;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The ball can not go above this point because vertical velocity is zero at this point.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;By the third equation of motion in the y-direction&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;v&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; = u&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; - 2 g H&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;0 = (u sin&amp;theta;)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; - 2 g H&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(H = \frac{{{u^2}{{\sin }^2}θ }}{{2g}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So the correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; option 4.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;time of flight of projectile&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is given by:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(T = \frac{2usinθ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where u is the&amp;nbsp;velocity, makes an angle &amp;#39;&amp;theta;&amp;#39; with the x-axis, and g is the gravitational acceleration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;range of flight&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(R = \frac{u^2sin2θ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where u is the&amp;nbsp;velocity,&amp;nbsp;makes an angle &amp;#39;&amp;theta;&amp;#39; with the x-axis, and g is the gravitational acceleration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Projectile motion:&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;A&amp;nbsp;kind of&amp;nbsp;motion that is&amp;nbsp;experienced by an object when it&amp;nbsp;is projected near the Earth&amp;#39;s surface and it moves along a curved path under the action of gravitational force.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;maximum height a projectile&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;can attain:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(H = \frac{{u_y^2}}{{2g}} = \frac{{{u^2}{{\sin }^2}θ }}{{2g}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where u is the&amp;nbsp;velocity that makes an angle &amp;#39;&amp;theta;&amp;#39; with the x-axis, and g is the gravitational acceleration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a particle&amp;nbsp;moves in projectile motion, its&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;velocity has two components.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ol style=&quot;margin-left: 40px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;​​vertical component (u sin&amp;theta;) = u&lt;sub&gt;x&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;horizontal component (u cos&amp;theta;) = u&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F2_J.K_Madhu_04.05.20__D3.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 413px; height: 238px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let the maximum height attained by the projectile is H,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At the maximum height, the ball will have zero velocity in vertical&amp;nbsp;direction i.e. v&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt; = 0;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The ball can not go above this point because vertical velocity is zero at this point.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;By the third equation of motion in the y-direction&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;v&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; = u&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; - 2 g H&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;0 = (u sin&amp;theta;)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; - 2 g H&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(H = \frac{{{u^2}{{\sin }^2}θ }}{{2g}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So the correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; option 4.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;time of flight of projectile&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is given by:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(T = \frac{2usinθ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where u is the&amp;nbsp;velocity, makes an angle &amp;#39;&amp;theta;&amp;#39; with the x-axis, and g is the gravitational acceleration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;range of flight&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(R = \frac{u^2sin2θ}{g}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where u is the&amp;nbsp;velocity,&amp;nbsp;makes an angle &amp;#39;&amp;theta;&amp;#39; with the x-axis, and g is the gravitational acceleration.&lt;/p&gt;
